{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3bec4fc4-6e57-4dbd-a552-819ff3542dec","content":"## What Changed\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, **implicit span conversions** now participate more broadly in overload resolution. For `int[]`, the compiler now prefers:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\nover the previous:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\nbecause `int[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<int>` is considered a better conversion than `int[]` → `IEnumerable<int>`. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees, causing the runtime failure.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nDisambiguate by either casting to `IEnumerable<int>` or calling `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:\n\n**Option A — cast the receiver:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — call the static method directly:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth force the compiler to bind to the expression-tree-compatible `Enumerable.Contains` overload instead of the `ReadOnlySpan` one.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6f94c329-4177-46a9-8182-ab60eff2d7e9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when compiled with `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), which changes how extension methods are resolved.\n\nBut more specifically, I think the issue is related to how `Enumerable.Contains()` is resolved for arrays. In .NET 9, `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]` would resolve to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)`. But in .NET 10, there might be a change.\n\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering - the breaking change could stem from new interfaces that arrays implement in .NET 10, or perhaps a new overload of `Contains` that's being preferred during method resolution. It might also be related to params collections or collection expressions changes, or possibly new `MemoryExtensions` methods that are now taking precedence over the traditional LINQ extension method.\n\nThe most likely culprit is that in .NET 10 / C# 14, when you call `array.Contains(num)`, the compiler is now resolving it to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` with a `Span<T>` or `ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameter instead of the `Enumerable.Contains` method. Since arrays implicitly convert to `Span<T>`, this conversion might be considered a better match now, but the problem is that `Span<T>` is a ref struct and can't be used in expression trees.\n\nHowever, I'm realizing that if the compiler tried to use a ref struct in an expression tree, it should fail at compile time, not runtime. But the user says it throws at runtime after calling `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`. So the expression tree itself must be building successfully somehow, which means either the runtime behavior of `Enumerable.Contains` changed in .NET 10, or there's something about how the expression tree interpreter handles certain method calls that's causing the issue. Let me reconsider what's actually happening here—in earlier versions like C# 13 / .NET 9, `array.Contains(num)` in an expression tree would resolve to `Enumerable.Contains<int>`, but maybe that's no longer the case. I'm realizing the core issue: in .NET 10, the compiler might resolve `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` instead of the `Enumerable` version due to improved overload resolution, but expression trees can't represent ref struct operations, so this should fail at compile time unless the tree is being constructed so